english:
  title: The Willows of Jiangnan
  author: Jeong Mongju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    O willows of Jiangnan, willows of Jiangnan,
    Spring breezes set your golden threads dancing and swaying.
    Year after year the willows of Jiangnan wear beauty—
    Yet when shall the wanderer of Jiangnan return home?

    The vast sea stretches endless, waves rising ten thousand fathoms high.
    Home lies distant, beyond the very edge of heaven.
    He who dwells at heaven's edge watches night and day
    For the returning ship upon the dark waters.
    Sitting before fallen blossoms, he can only sigh and sigh again.

    Longing's anguish—yes, he knows it well.
    But who could understand the hardship of these roads?
    O do not make your life a journey of endless wandering!
    For already the hair at a young man's temples
    Has turned white as snow.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Jiangnan (江南) refers to the region south of the Yangtze River, traditionally a symbol of beauty, refinement, and longing in East Asian poetry.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem employs the classical conceit of the traveler separated from home, expressing the poet's personal sorrow through landscape imagery—a common device in both Chinese and Korean classical poetry.
